## Code Review

這次的提交包含了大規模的重構，做得很好！特別是將狀態從 `HomeBottomView` 提升到 `Home`，並引入了由 Gemini 驅動、帶有確認步驟（`TaskSelectionOverlay`）的新任務創建流程，這大大改善了狀態管理和用戶體驗。`ErrorToastView` 的加入也為錯誤處理提供了更清晰的用戶反饋。

我留下了一條關於 `Keys.xcconfig` 中硬編碼 API 金鑰的**嚴重**級別評論，這出於安全考量必須立即處理。此外，我也指出了幾個中等級別的問題，涉及硬編碼的用戶 ID、JSON 解析的簡化機會，以及日誌記錄和程式碼健壯性的提升空間。

另外，新程式碼中散佈了許多 `print` 語句（例如在 `Home.swift`、`GeminiService.swift` 中）。雖然這在調試時很有用，但在合併到主分支前應將其移除或替換為正式的日誌框架，以保持控制台輸出的整潔。

big-refactor(sketchybar:stopwatch): Simplify stopwatch to use sketchybar updates instead of background processes

Major simplification of the stopwatch system:
- Eliminated background processes using sketchybar's update_freq mechanism
- Integrated mode rendering and cycling into main stopwatch.sh
- Removed redundant scripts (render_stopwatch_modes.sh, stopwatch_toggle_mode.sh)
- Added smooth mode highlighting updates without re-rendering
- Updated Hammerspoon keybindings to work with new system

Changes:
- No more PID tracking or orphaned processes
- Dynamic update frequency (1Hz when running, 0Hz when stopped)
- ~60% code reduction (from 7+ scripts to 2)
- Alt+M now smoothly cycles modes without visual flicker

fix: Restore stopwatch appearance when reloading sketchybar with timer running

When sketchybar reloads while a timer is running, properly restore:
- Mode icon and colors
- Background color based on current mode
- Correct text color (black on yellow, white on others)

This ensures the timer continues seamlessly after reload with full visual state.

visual artifacts during sketchybar reload.

issue.title: Inconsistent tagging of slicing-related plugins
issue.body:
While searching plugins that implement OctoPrint's slicing functionality, I noticed that they are tagged inconsistently, which makes them harder to find.

Current state:
- [PrePrintService](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/preprintservice/): tags `slic3r`, `slicing`
- [Slic3r](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/slic3r/): tag `slic3r`
- [Full-featured Slicer](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/slicer/): tag `slicer`
- [CuraEngine Legacy](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/curalegacy/): tag `slicer`

It would be useful to unify the tagging of slicing-related plugins (e.g. consistently using either `slicer` or `slicing`, what you prefer) in order to improve discoverability.

In addition, I noticed that a new plugin called InternalSlicer was recently created. In [this forum discussion](https://community.octoprint.org/t/plugin-octoprint-internal-slicer/57514), I invited the maintainer to add it to this repository as well.

comment.body: added the slicer tag to the two that didn't have that in above PR. as for the unregistered plugin, I agree would be great to have that other one as well, but it's the plugin's maintainer that is responsible for registering their plugin, acknowledging the expected responsibilities of such.

import collections

pull_request.title: fix: handle locals() calls in wrapped modules by static analysis
pull_request.body:
## Summary

This PR fixes bundling of modules that use `locals()` to dynamically access imported symbols, a pattern used by libraries like httpx to set `__module__` attributes.

## Changes

- **Static analysis for `locals()` calls**: When a module-level `locals()` call is detected, it's replaced with a statically determined dictionary containing all module-level symbols
- **`__all__` reference detection**: Added detection for when `__all__` variable is referenced elsewhere in the module (e.g., in loops), ensuring it's preserved when needed
- **AST builder enhancement**: Added `dict()` and `dict_item()` helper functions to the ast_builder for cleaner dictionary construction
- **Test fixture**: Added test case based on httpx's pattern of using `locals()` to access imported symbols

## Problem & Solution

The issue occurred when bundling modules that use this pattern:
```python
from ._internal import MyClass, my_func
__all__ = ["MyClass", "my_func"]
__locals = locals()  # Capture module-level locals
for __name in __all__:
    setattr(__locals[__name], "__module__", "mypkg")
```

In the bundled wrapper function, `locals()` returns function-local variables, not the imported symbols which are now global. The solution uses static analysis to determine what `locals()` would return at module level and replaces it with a dictionary literal containing the correct symbols.

## Test Results

- ✅ All existing tests pass
- ✅ New test fixture for the httpx pattern works correctly
- ✅ Clippy validation passes (only unused `dict_item` warning, kept for future use)
